<HEADLINE>
<P>
DAVIS SCHOOL FUNDS BILL IS BACKED; 
</P>
<P>
EDUCATION: A PLAN TO PAY FOR NEW SCHOOLS BY RAISING THE SALES TAX FINDS 
EDUCATORS, BUILDERS AND ANTONOVICH IN ACCORD AT A SANTA CLARITA 'SUMMIT.' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE PADILLA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a rare show of unanimity, Santa Clarita Valley school officials, developers 
and Los Angeles County Supervisor Mike Antonovich on Friday threw their support 
behind a bill by state Sen. Ed Davis (R-Santa Clarita) that would increase the 
state sales tax to raise funds for building schools. 
</P>
<P>
The bill calls for an amendment to the state Constitution to increase the sales 
tax a quarter-cent per dollar for 10 years. It also would make it easier for 
local school districts to increase property taxes to build schools in rapidly 
growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the Santa Clarita Valley's five school districts and the 
Building Industry Assn. of Southern California met with Davis and Antonovich at 
an education "summit" organized by Antonovich to develop a strategy to address 
school crowding statewide. 
</P>
<P>
Several bills aimed at raising money for school construction are pending in the 
Legislature, and Antonovich said he wants schools and builders to agree on 
which measures the county should endorse. 
</P>
<P>
Friday's meeting ended in harmony, quite unlike a similar meeting last week 
that broke up after 15 minutes when Antonovich learned that school officials 
and builders had not yet agreed on a joint recommendation to combat school 
crowding. The builders and school officials said they did not realize that 
their recommendations were due that day. 
</P>
<P>
An angry Antonovich said the builders and school officials had failed to show 
leadership on the issue. School officials promptly accused Antonovich of 
lacking leadership, saying he was ignoring county school crowding problems 
while trying to address the issue at the state level. 
</P>
<P>
But Friday's meeting was civil and businesslike. School officials and 
developers handed Antonovich their recommendations, and Davis outlined the 
provisions of his education bill. 
</P>
<P>
"The genius of this bill is that it goes for 10 years," Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
The quarter-cent sales tax would provide a steady and reliable source of funds 
for new schools, Davis said. California's school construction program now 
relies on statewide bond measures, which must be approved by the voters. A bond 
measure that would raise $800 million is on the June state ballot. 
</P>
<P>
The sales tax would be more cost-effective than bonds because the state must 
pay interest on bonds, he said. It takes $2.1 billion, Davis said, to pay off 
$800 million in bonds. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a stupid thing for anyone to do," Davis said. "It's an idiot's way." 
</P>
<P>
Under the Davis bill, school districts could raise property taxes up to 5 cents 
for each $100 of assessed valuation if the increase were approved by more than 
half the votes cast in a district election. School districts now need a 
two-thirds yes vote to raise property taxes. 
</P>
<P>
Davis told Antonovich that an endorsement from the Board of Supervisors would 
help his cause in Sacramento, particularly among conservative lawmakers usually 
averse to tax increases. "The biggest problem we're going to face is Assembly 
Republicans," Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to supporting Davis' bill, the builders and school officials asked 
Antonovich to support measures that would streamline construction guidelines 
and procedures that local school districts must follow to build schools. 
</P>
<P>
Antonovich endorsed the basic elements of the Davis bill but said he has some 
reservations about extending the tax for 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
Antonovich said he will present the recommendations to the Board of Supervisors 
Tuesday. The board could vote on whether to support the package a week later. 
</P>
<P>
Friday's meeting concerned statewide solutions to school crowding but did not 
specifically address conditions in the Santa Clarita Valley, where the five 
districts predict they will need $400 million to build 33 new schools by 2010. 
</P>
<P>
Developers and Santa Clarita school officials have been at odds for more than a 
year over how much money the building industry should contribute to new 
schools. The districts are suing the Board of Supervisors to block construction 
of two housing developments in Castaic, arguing that supervisors have the power 
to deny building permits to projects that overburden schools and that they 
should use that power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
