<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAYING FOR STATE HIGHWAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two recent front-page articles, Douglas Shuit's "Tax Revolt: 1990: Hello 
Gridlock" (March 6) and William Trombley's "Age, Growth Take Heavy Toll on 
State," Feb. 11), discuss state government's struggle to maintain services and 
infrastructure in light of voter imposed limits on spending and taxation. 
</P>
<P>
While, both articles are generously sprinkled with quotes from frustrated 
elected officials and bureaucrats, little attention is given to the other side 
of the equation: How much can taxpayers afford? 
</P>
<P>
Government may need more money to keep up, but so do the people of California. 
</P>
<P>
For a generation and more, government in California has increased faster than 
the citizen's average personal income. Taxpayers pay for the roads and then 
must purchase and operate a car on those roads. Automobile costs are increasing 
33% faster than increases in California average worker incomes. We pay for 
services to our homes and for services for those who don't have homes, but the 
cost of a mortgage or rent or home repair is going through the roof. Only 16% 
of the people in Los Angeles have the required income to afford a median priced 
home. 
</P>
<P>
With taxpayers pushed to their financial limits just to keep up with costs of 
everyday living, other answers besides tax increases must be explored to solve 
government's problems. Privatization of government services to get more in 
return for each tax dollar is one promising alternative given little or no 
attention by the tax-and-spend lobby. 
</P>
<P>
JOEL FOX 
</P>
<P>
President, Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Assn. 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
