<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAYING FOR STATE HIGHWAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yes, there's a tax revolt. The reason is plain -- we are stressed out. Federal 
taxes are climbing for the former middle class, which is now the lower middle 
class. 
</P>
<P>
All our hopes for climbing the ladder are fading fast in the wake of the 
Reagan-Bush tax gifts to the rich, combined with the failure of the famous 
Reagan trickle-down theory. 
</P>
<P>
I would vote for the 9-cent gas tax if it would provide public transportation 
and road maintenance, but I don't want to see any more freeways built. New 
roads will service the new people, who are clearly not paying enough taxes to 
build roads to service their needs, and will not answer the problem anyway -- a 
new road quickly exceeds its capacity, and the only solution then is to build 
more roads. 
</P>
<P>
We need more health care, schools, police and jails, and more housing because 
our population increases, directly or indirectly, lead to more illness, 
children and crime, and a terrific housing shortage. All this is true because 
demand far exceeds supply. The only possibility, then, is to cut the demand. 
</P>
<P>
The common theme here is our skyrocketing population. We are not managing the 
astonishing growth of this state, which is why Californians are crying loudly 
for better urban planning. 
</P>
<P>
We must do something about it before we all become New Yorkers. 
</P>
<P>
CATHERINE A. STROHLEIN 
</P>
<P>
San Diego 
</P>
</TEXT>
