<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP BASKETBALL STATE CHAMPIONSHIPS; 
</P>
<P>
MATER DEI VS. RIORDAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RECORDS -- Mater Dei (33-1), Riordan (29-2) 
</P>
<P>
SITE -- Oakland Coliseum Arena, 7 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
MATER DEI UPDATE -- A last-second three-point basket by guard Jason Quinn gave 
Mater Dei a 46-45 victory over Long Beach Poly in the regional championship 
last Saturday. It was the Monarchs' 25th consecutive victory and put them in 
their second state title game. Mater Dei won the 1987 state title behind the 
play of center LeRon Ellis. This year's team features a balanced attack with 
five players averaging between nine and 15.8 points per game. Guard David Boyle 
is the team's leading scorer, but forward Charlie Andres has been the 
difference in the playoffs. Andres is averaging 12 points and 12 rebounds per 
game in eight postseason games. Coach Gary McKnight, who has compiled a 226-19 
record in eight years, has missed practice this week after suffering severe 
muscle spasms in his back, but said he will be in Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
RIORDAN UPDATE -- A solid defense and the one-two scoring punch of forward 
Dwayne Fontana and guard Dorian Manigo have carried Riordan to its first state 
title appearance. Riordan allowed an average of only 55.6 points per game in 
three regional games. Riordan has won 11 consecutive games. Its only losses 
this season were to Los Angeles Fremont, 76-73, in the Amador Valley tournament 
and to Archbishop Mitty, 69-66, in a West Catholic Athletic League game. 
Fontana, who has signed with Arizona State, is the team's best player. He 
averages 22 points and 12 rebounds per game. Manigo, who has signed with Cal 
State Northridge, averages 19.1 points and four rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
KEY TO THE GAME -- Mater Dei must avoid the false security that some previous 
Southern California Regional winners have taken to Oakland. Granted, Southern 
Regional winners have won eight consecutive state titles, but Northern teams 
traditionally play inspired games in front of partisan crowds. Riordan's key 
players, Fontana and Manigo, must avoid foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
CONSENSUS -- Mater Dei isn't planning to leave the Bay Area until Monday night. 
Could this mean a long victory celebration has been planned? Why not? Mater Dei 
has too much height and depth for a two-man team like Riordan's, but the game 
will be closer than most expect. Mater Dei by six. 
</P>
</TEXT>
