<HEADLINE>
<P>
'THE HANDMAID'S TALE' AS A COMMENTARY ON ABORTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his on-the-mark review of "The Handmaid's Tale" (March 7), Peter Rainer 
refers to abortion only once, somewhat obliquely. 
</P>
<P>
Did he miss the fact that the movie was an attempt to be a commentary on 
abortion? Or was he just confused about what the message was and therefore left 
the subject untouched? If so, I don't blame him. 
</P>
<P>
The only way I knew the film was a pro-abortion effort was because the 
director, Volker Schlondorff, spoke at the Los Angeles premiere and made his 
intent clear. 
</P>
<P>
The movie backfired on him, though. The dismal future world it portrays is one 
that is the logical extension of unfettered abortion. If every woman is 
entitled to abortion, then all women are entitled to abortion, and we have 
delegated to pregnant women the right to extinguish the species. In the film, 
only 1 in 100 women can have children; it's a short step from that to "1 in 100 
will have a child." 
</P>
<P>
KEVIN R. DAVIS, Beverly Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
