<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: OXNARD; 
</P>
<P>
BAKERY NOW MEETS STATE HEALTH CODE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PEGGY LEE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After a rare conviction for violating state health laws, the LA Central Bakery 
in Oxnard was found to be in compliance after an inspection was conducted this 
week, according to a prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
Charges were brought against the firm at 600 Meta St. after investigations in 
August and November by the state Department of Health Services revealed that 
the bakery was unsanitary, said Deputy Dist. Atty. 
</P>
<P>
Jeff Bennett. 
</P>
<P>
The bakery was also selling tortillas and other foods that did not meet legal 
standards of purity and processing, Bennett said. 
</P>
<P>
The bakery and its chief executive officer, Frank Rodriguez, pleaded no contest 
to misdemeanor violations and were sentenced last month to three years 
probation. A summary probation does not require reporting to a probation 
officer. They were also ordered to pay a fine of $500 each. 
</P>
<P>
Bennett said while he suspected many establishments were in violation of the 
Health and Safety Code, the conviction was "a little unusual." 
</P>
<P>
The bakery had been given two warnings before charges were filed, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Photographs taken by health inspectors showed that the ceiling was 
deteriorating in some places, the kitchen floors were dirty and parts of the 
refrigerator were rusting, he said. PEGGY LEE 
</P>
</TEXT>
