<P>
NEW YORK; 
</P>
<P>
EYEWITNESS INDICTED IN FATAL ATTACK CASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An eyewitness in the killing of a black teen-ager who decided at the last 
moment not to testify against his friends was charged with 2nd-degree murder in 
the slaying. 
</P>
<P>
John Vento, 21, was charged with intentional murder and showing a depraved 
indifference to human life in the August, 1989, slaying of Yusuf Hawkins in 
Brooklyn. Vento's decision forced a postponement in the trial, and it was seen 
as a major blow to the prosecution's efforts to build cases against the seven 
others charged. Hawkins and three others had gone to the predominantly white 
Brooklyn neighborhood of Bensonhurst to look at a used car when they were 
attacked by baseball-bat-wielding white youths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
